eparate ISA symbols are used Disjoint specialization An entity may belong to at most one specialized entity set arrows to a shared ISA symbol in the diagram Attributes ¶ Lower-level entity types inherit : attributes of the higher-level entity type participation in relationship types of the higher-level entity type Lower-level entity types can : have attributes participate in relationship types that the higher-level entity does not participate in Participation Constraints ¶ Total generalization/specialization Each higher-level entity must belong to a lower-level entity type Notation: double line Partial generalization/specialization (default) Each higher-level can (may or may not) belong to a lower-level entity type Alternative Notations ¶ For alternative notations see DBS3 slides p 108 Mapping Basic Concepts to Relations ¶ Entities correspond to nouns, relationships to verbs Each statement in the requirement specification should be reflected somewhere in the ER schema Each ER diagram (ERD) should be located somewhere in the requirement specification Conceptual design often reveals inconsistencies and ambiguities in the requirement specification, which must first be resolved. Basic Approach For each entity type 	o 	o relation Name of the entity type 	o 	o name of the relation Attributes of the entity type 	o 	o Attributes of the relation Primary key of the entity type 	o 	o Primary key of the relation We do not care about the order of attributes in this context! Mapping of N:M Relationship Types ¶ Basic Approach New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add the primary key attributes of all involved entity types Primary keys of involved entity types together become the key of the new relation  old{takes}:\{[\underline{	ext{studID} 	o 	ext{student}}, \underline{	ext{courseID} 	o 	ext{course}}]\}  old{takes}:\{[\underline{	ext{studID} 	o 	ext{student}}, \underline{	ext{courseID} 	o 	ext{course}}]\} Key attributes "imported" from involved entity types (relations) are called foreign keys In General ¶ Mapping of 1:N Relationship Types ¶ Basic Approach New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add the primary key attributes of all involved entity types Primary key of the "N"-side becomes the key in the new relation Initial  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ & old{teaches} &&: \{[\underline{	ext{courseID}	o 	ext{course}}, 	ext{empID} 	o 	ext{professor}]\} \end{align*}  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ & old{teaches} &&: \{[\underline{	ext{courseID}	o 	ext{course}}, 	ext{empID} 	o 	ext{professor}]\} \end{align*} Improved by Merging  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}, \color{darkred}{	ext{taughtBy} 	o 	ext{professor}}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ \end{align*}  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}, \color{darkred}{	ext{taughtBy} 	o 	ext{professor}}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ \end{align*} Relations with the same key can be combined, but only these and no others! If the participation is not total , merging requires null values for the foreign key. In such cases, it might be preferable for some applications to have a separate relation. Mapping of 1:1 Relationship Types ¶ New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add primary key attributes of all involved entity types Primary key of any of the involved entity types can become the key in the new relation Initial  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\underline{vineyard}, address}\ elational{owns}{\underline{licenseID 	o license}, vineyard 	o producer}	ext{ or}\ elational{owns}{licenseID 	o license, \underline{vineyard 	o producer}} \end{align*}  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\underline{vineyard}, address}\ elational{owns}{\underline{licenseID 	o license}, vineyard 	o producer}	ext{ or}\ elational{owns}{licenseID 	o license, \underline{vineyard 	o producer}} \end{align*} Improvement  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount, ownedBy 	o producer}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address} \end{align*}  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount, ownedBy 	o producer}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address} \end{align*} Or  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address, ownsLicense 	o license} \end{align*}  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address, ownsLicense 	o license} \end{align*} It is best to extend a relation of an entity type with total participation Summary: Mapping Relationship Types to Relations ¶ M:N New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add attributes referencing the primary keys of the involved entity type relations Primary key: set of foreign keys 1:N Add information to the entity type relation of the “N”-side: Add foreign key referencing the primary key of the “1”-side entity type relation Add attributes of the relationship type 1:1 Add information to one of the involved entity type relations: Add foreign key referencing the primary key of the other entity type relation Add attributes of the relationship type Foreign Keys ¶ A foreign key is an attribute (or a combination of attributes) of a relation that references the primary key (or candidate key) of another relation Example elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy 	o professor}} elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy 	o professor}} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} Here \mathrm{taughtBy} \mathrm{taughtBy} is a foreign key referencing relation professor Alternative Notation elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy}} elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy}} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} Foreign key: \mathrm{course.taughtBy 	o professor.empID} \mathrm{course.taughtBy 	o professor.empID} Notation for composite keys: \{R.A_1, R.A_2\} 	o \{S.B_1, S.B_2\} \{R.A_1, R.A_2\} 	o \{S.B_1, S.B_2\} Mapping Additional Concepts to Relations ¶ Weak Entity Types ¶ Entities of a weak entity type are existentially dependent on a strong entity type uniquely identifiable in combination with the strong entity type's key Mapping: New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add primary key attributes of all involved entity types Foreign key of the "N"-side becomes the key in the new relation Initially elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} elation{belongsTo}{\pk{name 	o wine, year 	o vintage}} elation{belongsTo}{\pk{name 	o wine, year 	o vintage}} Merged Weak entity types and their identifying relationship types can always be merged elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} More complex example in DBS3 slides p 157 Recursive Relationship Types ¶ Mapping just like standard N:M relationship types and renaming of foreign keys elation{area}{\pk{name}, region} elation{area}{\pk{name}, region} elation{border}{\pk{from	o area, to 	o area}} elation{border}{\pk{f