onumber Entities correspond to nouns, relationships to verbs Each statement in the requirement specification should be reflected somewhere in the ER schema Each ER diagram (ERD) should be located somewhere in the requirement specification Conceptual design often reveals inconsistencies and ambiguities in the requirement specification, which must first be resolved. Overview of the steps ¶ Regular entity type Create a relation, consider special attribute types Weak entity type Create a relation 1:1 binary relationship type Extend a relation with foreign key 1:N binary relationship type Extend a relation with foreign key N:M relationship type Create a relation N-ary relationship type Create a relation Basic Approach ¶ For each entity type 	o 	o relation Name of the entity type 	o 	o name of the relation Attributes of the entity type 	o 	o Attributes of the relation Primary key of the entity type 	o 	o Primary key of the relation We do not care about the order of attributes in this context! Mapping of N:M Relationship Types ¶ Basic Approach New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add the primary key attributes of all involved entity types Primary keys of involved entity types together become the key of the new relation  old{takes}:\{[\underline{	ext{studID} 	o 	ext{student}}, \underline{	ext{courseID} 	o 	ext{course}}]\}  old{takes}:\{[\underline{	ext{studID} 	o 	ext{student}}, \underline{	ext{courseID} 	o 	ext{course}}]\} Key attributes "imported" from involved entity types (relations) are called foreign keys Mapping of 1:N Relationship Types ¶ Basic Approach New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add the primary key attributes of all involved entity types Primary key of the "N"-side becomes the key in the new relation Initial  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ & old{teaches} &&: \{[\underline{	ext{courseID}	o 	ext{course}}, 	ext{empID} 	o 	ext{professor}]\} \end{align*}  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ & old{teaches} &&: \{[\underline{	ext{courseID}	o 	ext{course}}, 	ext{empID} 	o 	ext{professor}]\} \end{align*} Improved by Merging  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}, \color{darkred}{	ext{taughtBy} 	o 	ext{professor}}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ \end{align*}  egin{align*} & old{course} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{courseID}}, 	ext{title}, 	ext{ects}, \color{darkred}{	ext{taughtBy} 	o 	ext{professor}}]\}\ & old{professor} &&:\{[\underline{	ext{empID}}, 	ext{name}, 	ext{rank},	ext{office}]\}\ \end{align*} Relations with the same key can be combined, but only these and no others! If the participation is not total , merging requires null values for the foreign key. In such cases, it might be preferable for some applications to have a separate relation. Mapping of 1:1 Relationship Types ¶ New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add primary key attributes of all involved entity types Primary key of any of the involved entity types can become the key in the new relation Initial  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\underline{vineyard}, address}\ elational{owns}{\underline{licenseID 	o license}, vineyard 	o producer}	ext{ or}\ elational{owns}{licenseID 	o license, \underline{vineyard 	o producer}} \end{align*}  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\underline{vineyard}, address}\ elational{owns}{\underline{licenseID 	o license}, vineyard 	o producer}	ext{ or}\ elational{owns}{licenseID 	o license, \underline{vineyard 	o producer}} \end{align*} Improvement  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount, ownedBy 	o producer}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address} \end{align*}  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount, ownedBy 	o producer}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address} \end{align*} Or  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address, ownsLicense 	o license} \end{align*}  egin{align*} elational{license}{\underline{licenseID}, amount}\ elational{producer}{\pk{vineyard}, address, ownsLicense 	o license} \end{align*} It is best to extend a relation of an entity type with total participation Foreign Keys ¶ Foreign Keys ¶ A foreign key is an attribute (or a combination of attributes) of a relation that references the primary key (or candidate key) of another relation Example elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy 	o professor}} elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy 	o professor}} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} Here \mathrm{taughtBy} \mathrm{taughtBy} is a foreign key referencing relation professor Alternative Notation elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy}} elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects, \color{darkred}{taughtBy}} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} Foreign key: \mathrm{course.taughtBy 	o professor.empID} \mathrm{course.taughtBy 	o professor.empID} Notation for composite keys: \{R.A_1, R.A_2\} 	o \{S.B_1, S.B_2\} \{R.A_1, R.A_2\} 	o \{S.B_1, S.B_2\} Weak Entity Types ¶ Entities of a weak entity type are existentially dependent on a strong entity type uniquely identifiable in combination with the strong entity type's key Mapping: New relation with all attributes of the relationship type Add primary key attributes of all involved entity types Foreign key of the "N"-side becomes the key in the new relation Initially elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} elation{belongsTo}{\pk{name 	o wine, year 	o vintage}} elation{belongsTo}{\pk{name 	o wine, year 	o vintage}} Merged Weak entity types and their identifying relationship types can always be merged elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{wine}{color,\pk{name}} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} elation{vintage}{\pk{name	o wine, year}, residualSweetness} More complex example in DBS3 slides p 157 Recursive Relationship Types ¶ Mapping just like standard N:M relationship types and renaming of foreign keys elation{area}{\pk{name}, region} elation{area}{\pk{name}, region} elation{border}{\pk{from	o area, to 	o area}} elation{border}{\pk{from	o area, to 	o area}} Recursive Functional Relationship Types ¶ Mapping just like standard 1:N relationship types and merging elation{critic}{\pk{name}, organization, mentor 	o critic} elation{critic}{\pk{name}, organization, mentor 	o critic} N-ary Relationship Types ¶ Entity Types All participating entity types are mapped according to the standard rules elation{critic}{\pk{name}, organization} elation{critic}{\pk{name}, organization} elation{dish}{\pk{description}, sideOrder} elation{dish}{\pk{description}, sideOrder} elation{wine}{color, \pk{WName}, year, residualSweetness} elation{wine}{color, \pk{WName}, year, residualSweetness} N-ary Relationship Types (N:M:P) elation{recommends}{\pk{WName 	o wine, description 	o dish, name 	o critic}} elation{recommends}{\pk{WName 	o wine, description 	o dish, name 	o critic}} N:M:1 Relationship Type ¶ Relations elation{student}{\pk{studID}, name, semester} elation{student}{\pk{studID}, name, semester} elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects} elation{course}{\pk{courseID}, title, ects} elation{professor}{\pk{empID}, name, rank, office} elation{